\details{
\subsection{The Core Idea}{

In a one-sample mean test, we are asking: \emph{"Is the average value we
observed in our sample consistent with some claimed population mean, or
is it too far away to be explained by random chance alone?"}

The null hypothesis always takes the form H\eqn{_0}: \eqn{\mu =} \code{null_mu},
where \eqn{\mu} (Greek letter "mu") represents the \strong{true, unknown
population mean}.
}

\subsection{Z-Test vs. T-Test (Theory Method)}{

When \code{method = "theory"}, the choice between Z and T depends entirely on
what you know about the population:
\itemize{
\item If the \strong{true population standard deviation} (\eqn{\sigma}) \strong{is known}
(\code{sd_type = "population"}), use the \strong{Z-test}.
\item If only the \strong{sample standard deviation} (s) is available
(\code{sd_type = "sample"}), use the \strong{T-test}. This is the most common
real-world situation. The degrees of freedom are handled automatically
in the background.
}
}

\subsection{Simulation Method (Parametric Bootstrap)}{

We simulate what the world would look like \emph{if the null hypothesis were
true} by repeatedly drawing samples of size \code{n} from a Normal distribution
centered at \code{null_mu} with standard deviation \code{sd_val}. The SD of that
simulated null distribution goes in the denominator of the test statistic.
The p-value is the proportion of simulated sample means as extreme as or
more extreme than our observed \eqn{\bar{x}}.
}

\subsection{Validity Conditions for Theory Method}{

The theory-based test is most reliable when:
\itemize{
\item Sample size \eqn{n \geq 20} (Central Limit Theorem kicks in), \strong{or}
\item The underlying distribution of the variable is known to be roughly
symmetric even for smaller samples.
}

A warning will be issued automatically if \code{n < 20} and
\code{method = "theory"}.
}
}
